The photophysical properties of CB-I were characterized in detail. The UV–vis absorption spectrum of CB-I is in Fig. 2
                        a exhibits an absorption band in the range of 300–400 nm which is mainly attributed to the n-π* transition of C=O. Fig. 2a displays the fluorescence emission centered at 439 nm with an excitation wavelength of 394 nm and the afterglow emission centered at 438 nm with an excitation wavelength of 392 nm (Table 1
                        ). Intense blue emission was observed in CB-I which has been considered fluorescence under the 365 nm UV lamp (Fig. 2g). CB-I exhibits an obvious fluorescence excitation-independent characteristic with a maximal emission peak at 439 nm (Fig. 2b) and a high PLQY of 66.59% with a fluorescence lifetime of 4.16 ns. (Fig. S1, Table S1). This indicates only one chromophore structure exists on the surface of CB-I [40,42] and some luminescence centers are eliminated at high temperatures [41]. Moreover, the afterglow emission spectrum of CB-I also indicates excitation-independent behaviors (Fig. 2c) with purple light at 392 nm as the excitation wavelength, which is consistent with the fluorescence emission spectrum (Table 1). After turning off the 365 nm UV lamp, the cyan afterglow could be observed for 5 s by the naked eye (Fig. 2g) and an ultra-high afterglow quantum yield of 35.07% was obtained (Fig. S2). The novelty is that there was an easily overlooked peak at 490 nm in the afterglow emission spectrum (Fig. 2a, Table 1), which implies the afterglow emission of CB-I may have dual-mode afterglow emission rather than a simple room-temperature phosphorescence emission. It can be inferred that the afterglow emission peak at 438 nm belongs to the delayed fluorescence (DF) [43] and the other at 490 nm is the emission peak of phosphorescence since the fluorescence emission spectrum and afterglow emission spectrum of CB-I are highly overlapped at around 438 nm. To further verify the above conjecture and confirm the origin of the afterglow emission in the CB-I composites, the temperature-dependent afterglow emission spectrum (Fig. 2d) was monitored. At 80 K, CB-I exhibits a single emission at 490 nm and the intensity of the peak gradually decreases with the elevation of temperature, as is typical characteristic of phosphorescence. It should be noted that high temperature is incapable of effectively limiting the vibration and activates the non-radiative transition to a great extent, thereby weakening the phosphorescence emission [44,45]. A new peak at 438 nm appeared as the temperature continued to climb until reached 230 K. As expected above speculation, the intensity of the peak at 438 nm gradually increased with temperature from 230 K to 310 K, confirming the emission at 438 nm was indeed delayed fluorescence. Therefore, the intensity of phosphorescence emission weakened and the delayed fluorescence emission enhanced as the temperature continued to rise from 80 K, leading to the progressive conversion of RTP to DF. The afterglow lifetimes of DF and RTP at ambient conditions were measured and fitted to be 180.5 ms and 193.5 ms, respectively (Fig. 2e, Table S2, Table S3).
